          "body": "Genesis structures itself with eleven 'these are the records of the generations of' (toledot) formulas. Each one closes a secondary figure's account before advancing the primary narrative. The Ishmael toledot (25:12-18) closed out Abraham's non-covenant son before Isaac's story dominated. Now the Esau toledot (36:1, 9) closes out Jacob's non-covenant twin before the Joseph narrative (37:2) opens. The formula is not dismissive — it is formal and respectful. The narrator gives Esau's descendants their own chapter, their own archive, their own official record. But having given it, the camera turns. The story of redemption runs through Jacob, not Esau. Genesis 36 is a deliberate act of canonical accounting before the narrative narrows to the line through which the Redeemer will come."
