          "body": "The equation 'Esau is Edom' is stated four times (36:1, 8, 19, 43). The name Edom ('red') connects to the red stew of 25:30 — the moment Esau despised his birthright. Now that birthright is permanently gone, and the name that memorializes its loss becomes the name of an entire nation. This is not merely ethnic labeling; it is a theological statement about how identity forms around decisive choices. Esau chose the immediate over the promised, Canaan's daughters over the covenant family, Seir over the land of promise. Those choices, multiplied across generations, produced the Edomite nation — a people who occupied territory, organized governance, and achieved military power, but did so outside the covenant line. Calvin's observation is apposite: God blessed Esau materially (Institutes, Commentary on Genesis 36) — fruitfulness, land, governance — as a fulfillment of the general blessing of Genesis 27:39-40, while the specific covenant blessing flowed through Jacob alone."
